{"award_age":57.0,"bio_image":"full\/d2be93cfc04b93ac7ffdf33888241172fbf3f5f6.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1947-01-29T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"female","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/1\/1f\/LindaBuck_cropped_1.jpg\/220px-LindaBuck_cropped_1.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Linda_B._Buck","mini_bio":"<p><b>Linda Brown Buck<\/b> (born January 29, 1947) is an <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_of_America\" title=\"United States of America\" class=\"mw-redirect\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biologist\" title=\"Biologist\">biologist<\/a> best known for her work on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Olfactory_system\" title=\"Olfactory system\">olfactory system<\/a>. She was awarded the 2004 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a>, along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Richard_Axel\" title=\"Richard Axel\">Richard Axel<\/a>, for their work on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Olfactory_receptor\" title=\"Olfactory receptor\">olfactory receptors<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Linda_B._Buck#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>In their landmark paper published in 1991, Buck and Axel <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cloning\" title=\"Cloning\">cloned<\/a> olfactory receptors, showing that they belong to the family of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/G_protein-coupled_receptor\" title=\"G protein-coupled receptor\" class=\"mw-redirect\">G protein-coupled receptors<\/a>. By analyzing <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rat\" title=\"Rat\">rat<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/DNA\" title=\"DNA\">DNA<\/a>, they estimated that there were approximately one thousand different <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gene\" title=\"Gene\">genes<\/a> for olfactory receptors in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mammal\" title=\"Mammal\">mammalian<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genome\" title=\"Genome\">genome<\/a>. This research opened the door to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetics\" title=\"Genetics\">genetic<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecular_biology\" title=\"Molecular biology\">molecular<\/a> analysis of the mechanisms of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Olfaction\" title=\"Olfaction\">olfaction<\/a>. In their later work, Buck and Axel have shown that each <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Olfactory_receptor_neuron\" title=\"Olfactory receptor neuron\">olfactory receptor neuron<\/a> remarkably only expresses one kind of olfactory receptor protein and that the input from all neurons expressing the same receptor is collected by a single dedicated <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Glomerulus_(olfaction)\" title=\"Glomerulus (olfaction)\">glomerulus<\/a> of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Olfactory_bulb\" title=\"Olfactory bulb\">olfactory bulb<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Linda B. Buck","place_of_birth":"Seattle, Washington","place_of_death":null,"text":"Linda B. Buck , Physiology or Medicine, 2004","year":2004.0}